   "source": [
    "This table lines up all three models on the same four metrics:\n",
    "- **R² / Adjusted R²**: higher means more salary variance explained — rising from 0.33 (Model 1) to 0.37 (Model 2) to 0.50 (Model 3).\n",
    "- **RMSE**: lower means more accurate dollar predictions; in percentage-of-median-salary terms, it drops from 32.1% (Model 1) to 31.1% (Model 2) to 27.9% (Model 3).\n",
    "- **MAE**: also lower-is-better, dropping from 24.3% to 23.4% to 20.4% of median salary across the same three models.\n",
    "\n",
    "Because Model 3 trains on the same engineered features as Model 2, any gap between them is attributable to the model itself (random forest vs. linear regression) rather than to differences in feature engineering. Across all three metrics, the largest single improvement comes from this model-type switch rather than from the feature changes introduced in Model 2.\n",
    "\n",
    "For anyone using this analysis to inform real decisions -- whether benchmarking a salary offer, setting pay bands, or flagging underpriced postings -- the practical takeaway is twofold. First, a non-linear model captures meaningfully more of the salary structure in this market than a linear one, so Model 3 should be the default choice when prediction accuracy matters most. Second, the linear models remain useful precisely because they are interpretable: Model 2's coefficients can tell a hiring manager \"this specific title is worth \\$X more,\" a statement Model 3 cannot make as directly. In practice, the two approaches complement each other -- Random Forest for the most accurate estimate, Multiple Linear Regression for explaining why that estimate looks the way it does."
